---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
import BlogBackButton from '../../components/BlogBackButton.astro';
import BlogBridgeLinks from '../../components/BlogBridgeLinks.astro';
import SourceList from '../../components/SourceList.astro';
import { evidenceLinks } from '../../data/evidence';
import { buildBlogPostingSchema } from '../../lib/seo';
import RelatedPosts from '../../components/RelatedPosts.astro';

const postSources = [
  {
    ...evidenceLinks.astroWhy,
    note: 'Astro emphasizes minimal client-side JavaScript for optimal speed.',
  },
  {
    ...evidenceLinks.googlePageExperience,
    note: 'Google strongly recommends meeting Core Web Vitals thresholds for ranking.',
  },
  {
    ...evidenceLinks.wixThirdPartyCode,
    note: 'Wix pages warn about the performance impact of heavy third-party code and bundled tools.',
  }
];

const articleImage = '/images/astro_vs_wix_cover.png';
const publishedTime = '2026-04-05T09:00:00-05:00';
const articleSchema = buildBlogPostingSchema({
  headline: 'Astro vs Wix — Why Service Businesses in NY, Florida & Texas Choose Custom',
  description: 'A practical comparison of Astro and Wix for SEO, page speed, and long-term flexibility — with examples from Naples, Houston, and Central NY.',
  path: '/blog/astro-vs-wix',
  image: articleImage,
  datePublished: publishedTime,
  articleSection: 'Web Performance',
  keywords: ['Astro', 'Wix', 'SEO', 'Naples web design', 'Houston web design', 'Core Web Vitals', 'Small business websites'],
});
---
<Layout
  title="Astro vs Wix for Local Service Sites | Designed by Anthony"
  description="A practical comparison of Astro and Wix for SEO, page speed, and long-term flexibility — with examples from Naples, Houston, and Central NY."
  image={articleImage}
  ogType="article"
  publishedTime={publishedTime}
  modifiedTime={publishedTime}
  articleSection="Web Performance"
  articleTags={['Astro', 'Wix', 'SEO', 'Speed', 'Naples FL', 'Houston TX']}
  schema={articleSchema}
  bodyClass="has-progress-bar"
>
  <article class="blog-post">
    <BlogBackButton />
    <div class="post-header">
      <div class="meta">
        <span>March 30, 2026</span> | <span>8 min read</span>
      </div>
      <h1>Astro vs Wix — Why Service Businesses in NY, Florida & Texas Choose Custom</h1>
    </div>
    
    <div class="post-image">
      <img src={articleImage} alt="Side-by-side comparison of Astro framework code architecture and Wix website builder interface highlighting performance and SEO differences" width="1024" height="1024" loading="eager" decoding="async" fetchpriority="high" />
    </div>

    <div class="post-content">
      <p>For a small business website, the platform matters because it affects speed, search visibility, and how much control you have later. Astro and Wix can both get a business online, but they solve very different problems. Astro is better when you want a fast, custom site with clean output. Wix is better when you want a visual editor and you are willing to trade some performance for convenience.</p>

      <p>That distinction matters more than most people think. A slow site can still look good in the editor and still cost you rankings, calls, and form fills in the real world. If the goal is a premium small business site that feels sharp on mobile and holds up in SEO, Astro usually gives you more room to win.</p>

      <h2>What Are Astro and Wix?</h2>
      <p>Astro is a modern web framework that ships mostly HTML by default and only loads JavaScript where it is actually needed. That makes it a strong fit for brochure sites, service business websites, blogs, and landing pages where speed matters. Wix is an all-in-one website builder with hosting, templates, and visual editing built in. It is easy to start with, especially for owners who want to update pages without touching code.</p>

      <p>Neither platform is automatically right or wrong. The real question is what kind of site you need and how important performance, flexibility, and ownership are to the business.</p>

      <h2>Where Astro Usually Wins</h2>
      <p>Astro is strong because it starts with less overhead. A small business site does not need to behave like a full web app just to show services, trust signals, FAQs, and a contact form. Astro lets you publish those pages with a much lighter front end, which usually means faster loads, better mobile performance, and a cleaner foundation for SEO.</p>

      <p>That matters most on service business sites where visitors arrive from search, skim quickly, and decide whether to call. A lighter page gives them the information faster and gives Google a cleaner page to crawl.</p>

      <h3>How Astro Helps Speed and Core Web Vitals</h3>
      <p>Astro's default approach is good for Core Web Vitals because it avoids shipping unnecessary JavaScript. Less code on the page usually means less work for the browser, especially on phones. That helps pages reach useful content faster and stay more stable while loading.</p>

      <p>It also gives you tighter control. If a page needs a form, a slider, or a testimonial carousel, those pieces can be added deliberately instead of shipping a heavy bundle to every visitor by default.</p>

      <h2>Where Wix Still Makes Sense</h2>
      <p>Wix is useful when speed is not the top priority and the owner values editing convenience more than technical control. For a simple site that mainly needs a homepage, an about page, a few services, and a contact form, Wix can be enough. It is also attractive when someone wants to log in, rearrange sections visually, and publish changes without developer help.</p>

      <p>The downside is that this convenience often comes with heavier output. That does not mean every Wix site is bad, but it does mean you have less control over what the browser downloads and how lean the final page really is.</p>

      <h2>SEO: The Real Difference Is Usually Performance and Control</h2>
      <p>Both Astro and Wix let you set titles, descriptions, headings, and basic SEO settings. The bigger difference is how much control you have over the final page. Astro gives you tighter control over markup, schema, internal linking patterns, and page weight. Wix gives you the basics, but you are working inside a platform that makes more decisions for you.</p>

      <p>For competitive local SEO, that extra control matters. It is easier to build cleaner service pages, stronger schema, more intentional content structure, and faster mobile experiences when the stack stays out of your way.</p>

      <h3>Structured Data and Technical SEO</h3>
      <p>Astro is especially nice when you want precise schema markup. You can build JSON-LD exactly the way you want, keep it consistent across templates, and avoid plugin clutter. Wix supports schema too, but custom implementations are usually less flexible and harder to scale cleanly across many page types.</p>

      <h2>Pricing, Ownership, and Long-Term Flexibility</h2>
      <p>Wix wraps editing, hosting, and the site builder into one subscription. That is convenient, but it also means you stay inside that ecosystem. Astro sites are usually deployed to a host like Netlify or Vercel, which gives you more control over how the site is published and maintained.</p>

      <p>For many small businesses, the bigger point is ownership. If you want a custom site that can grow with you, Astro gives you a cleaner path. If you mainly want to self-edit a starter website and do not mind platform limits, Wix can still work.</p>

      <h2>Which One Is Better for a Small Business Site?</h2>
      <p>If the goal is a fast, premium site built to rank, convert, and feel different from the local template crowd, Astro is the better choice. If the goal is quick setup and easy visual editing with less concern for top-tier performance, Wix can be enough.</p>

      <p>That is why I would frame it this way: Wix is a convenience-first website builder. Astro is a performance-first website foundation. For serious service businesses competing on trust and search visibility, the performance-first option usually ages better.</p>

      <h3>Why This Matters for Service Businesses in Naples, Houston, and Beyond</h3>
      <p>For a premium contractor in <a href="/service-areas/naples">Naples FL</a> selling to high-net-worth homeowners in Collier County, the Wix performance ceiling is especially costly. Affluent buyers research carefully, compare multiple businesses, and notice when a site feels slow or generic on their phone. A custom Astro build delivers the premium, sub-second experience that matches the quality of service these businesses sell. In <a href="/service-areas/houston">Houston</a>, where businesses cover sprawling territories from The Woodlands to Sugar Land, the flexibility to build distinct, lean service-area pages without shipping builder overhead to every visitor is the difference between ranking and being invisible.</p>
      <p>The same principle applies across <a href="/service-areas/manhattan">Manhattan</a>, where the competition density demands flawless mobile speed, and in markets like <a href="/service-areas/columbus">Columbus OH</a> and <a href="/service-areas/utica">Utica</a> where smaller businesses can punch above their weight with faster, cleaner sites than their template-heavy competitors.</p>

      <SourceList
        title="Sources"
        intro="The evidence behind the core tradeoffs in modern web frameworks."
        items={postSources}
      />
    </div>

    <BlogBridgeLinks />

    <RelatedPosts
      posts={[
        {
          title: 'Why We Build With Astro',
          href: '/blog/astro-tech-stack',
          description: 'Astro is a big reason our sites land at 98+ Lighthouse scores.',
          image: '/images/astro_rocket_cover.png',
          imageAlt: 'Developer coding at night',
          tag: 'Tech Stack',
        },
        {
          title: 'How Site Speed Impacts Revenue',
          href: '/blog/site-speed-conversion',
          description: 'Every second of load time costs you real conversions.',
          image: '/images/speed_conversion_cover.png',
          imageAlt: 'Analytics dashboard',
          tag: 'Performance',
        },
        {
          title: '5 Things Wrong With Contractor Websites',
          href: '/blog/contractor-website-mistakes',
          description: 'The most common mistakes that cost contractors leads.',
          image: '/images/contractor_mistakes_cover.png',
          imageAlt: 'Contractor at a laptop',
          tag: 'Web Design',
        },
      ]}
    />
  </article>
</Layout>

<style>
